000184_7be269c6-9c23-7672-fc43-9d7cd39d9d3c
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_7be269c6-9c23-7672-fc43-9d7cd39d9d3c" obligation="normative">
<title id="_044942ca-9796-b4a6-70f4-4ab0218662d2">Core</title>
<p id="_80d68486-bf75-c09f-fb55-52b4a4a52b90" anchor="core">This clause establishes the <strong>Core</strong> Requirements class, with IRI <tt>/req/core</tt>, which has a corresponding Conformance Class, <strong>Core</strong>, with IRI <tt>/conf/core</tt>.</p>

<p id="_9b3e584e-421e-c462-e012-c44bf69826f8">The Core module establishes a set of classes and properties which define the building blocks of a spatial reference system definition. Some of the definitions are extended in specialized modules related to the Core module.</p>

<clause id="_bcde7483-d7e8-90c9-129a-af8be87fc353" obligation="normative">
<title id="_334fa507-f3b2-6884-54bf-23cf005995ec">Coordinate System Module</title>
<p id="_0b1e9dfb-ceac-0f81-3e64-be8948e7efe0" anchor="cs">This clause establishes the <strong>CS</strong> Requirements class, with IRI <tt>/req/cs</tt>, which has a corresponding Conformance Class, <strong>CS</strong>, with IRI <tt>/conf/cs</tt>.</p>

<p id="_0db803d8-870a-85d8-5761-f10f6eaecbed">The coordinate system module introduces different types of coordinate systems which are dinstinguished in geospatial science and applications. Coordinate systems are distinguished by their area of use, i.e planetary or interstellar and by their multidimensionality.</p>

005954_d04c7936-eb44-8f43-f0d7-c189624e77af
Hanging paragraph in clause
<annex id="_d04c7936-eb44-8f43-f0d7-c189624e77af" obligation="normative">
<title id="_470614e0-369e-cd47-ac8c-e0c157b1a785">Abstract Test Suite</title>
<floating-title id="_6c4825b5-5b33-43be-8438-e76319911fee" depth="2" type="floating-title">A.0. Overview</floating-title>
<p id="_9b50ea30-51c1-09e4-2492-039aaaa61290">This Annex lists tests for the Conformance Classes defined in the main body sections of this Specification with links to their Requirements and test purpose method and type. Conformance classes may be used to signify the compatibility of a given implementation to parts of the CRS Ontology standard. They may be stated as part of a SPARQL 1.1 Service Description  <xref target="SPARQLSERVDESC"/> .</p>
